Inflation in Europe has been a disaster for food
The accelerated inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, prices in the 13 euro area countries rose more than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts said only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the key interest rate, saying that lower interest rates, with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
One analyst says it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we have to deter" inflation so that it does not have to intervene in the future.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has picked up because of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The market shares of cereal futures rose by 88 percent and the price of soybeans also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of edible oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price has risen 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold was worth almost $100.
According to the ECB, the inflation rate will fall from 2.1% this year to 2.5% in 2008, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the key rate twice in 2008.
Gallup reports a government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of Fidesz (Young Democrats Alliance) supporters increased significantly in early December, so that it now has the highest number of supporters since 2002, while Gallup (Poll Institute) has never before found such low socialist support, at 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, support of more than two thirds (71 percent) against support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of MPs: their support is two percent in the entire population.
Of the loyal voters who were sure to go to the polls, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate continued to deteriorate from the previous low, the proportion of those who considered the economic situation of the country to be particularly serious was never higher, rising to 41%, and according to a further 46% the situation was rather serious.
After the more optimistic outlook of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For the next year, the majority of the population expects the situation to worsen and only one tenth expects an improvement.
Last December, 71 percent of those polled, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, thought the prime minister was doing his job badly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 percent the Fidesz president.
One indicator of the change in the political situation is the proportion of the population who believe that dissatisfaction with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change of government.
While 35 percent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office after the riots in October last year, only 20 percent now believe that holding new elections would be the solution.
When asked about their intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents say they would certainly vote and an additional 20 percent say they would probably vote.
By comparison, for a "parliamentary election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and an additional 15 percent would probably participate.
74 percent of people would say no to tuition fees for higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital costs.
When we look only at the same proportions of people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of voters respectively would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital costs.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs shopping triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 per cent from last year, although the VAT rate did not increase this year.
The article by Napi Gazdaság (Economy of the Day)
This year, in the Budaörs shopping triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, with a value increase of well over a thousand forints in all hypermarkets.
Prices, which had already skyrocketed in supermarkets in December last year, have not risen sharply from their previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below 9,000 forints last year now cost more than 10,000 forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 HUF, at least the psychological threshold of ten thousand HUF.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573.
(In 2003, this was HUF 6,800.)
Prices for unicum and live fish have remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillets, walnuts and poppies have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Statistical Institute), but at Auchan, one kilo of bread was found at only HUF 139.
Competition did not bring the price of the product below 200 HUF.
It was surprising to see that in this hypermarket too the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was under 200 forints, so that the bottle cost only 257 forints.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora raised the price of her daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan raised them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
When we compare the most expensive basket of last year and the cheapest basket of this year, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between the cheapest basket of last year and the most expensive basket of this year is 21 percent.
Prices have risen by an average of HUF 1,480 a year.
Last year prices rose by an average of HUF 1 206 although the impact of the increase in the VAT rate was already being felt in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has left trade confused, hypermarkets cannot clearly determine which margin to apply to products as they are unable to foresee the impact of price changes on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the turnover of a product, he may lose a large profit on the margin appropriate to the intensity of the trade.)
The change in the VAT rate led to such an excessive increase in the prices of the Daily Basket that the most expensive basket was HUF 1 720 higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only HUF 844.
This year the difference was not so great, as the most expensive basket was worth HUF 1 630 more than last year and the cheapest basket also increased by HUF 1 284.
As we approach the two Christmas seasons, we see a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer goods have risen by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic foodstuffs, the Statistical Institute has recorded a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and eggs.)
According to the newspaper, this seems almost absurd, since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent from the base.
The indices show that flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the price surge accepted by the multinationals as well.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets don't complain, they're consistently having good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets they visited.
They buy everything in bulk, they take the long-term food on pallets.
On Wednesday morning, large queues formed at the cash registers of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the provinces, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for durable consumer goods.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
Hygiene in hospitals, insufficient beds, and overwork of medical personnel are not helping to prevent infections, says the chief physician of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals also save on disinfectants
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected in a man hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
Earlier this year, a similar infection occurred at the same location.
The man who was seriously injured in a car accident was released from the hospital but soon afterwards had to return to the hospital because of an MRSA infection and since then doctors have been unable to perform a major operation on him because of the bacteria in his body.
As of 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National Hospital Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer at the National Centre for Epidemiology.
That is, the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics and are easily cured.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria that will multiply quickly in poor hospital conditions.
If the immune system is temporarily or prolonged, the bacteria can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, underweight or debilitated patients.
According to the chief medical officer of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of daily life in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, because MRSA is not found only there or not looked for, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The ASs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the healthcare staff are wearing rubber gloves and protective masks and we have appropriate antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, patients in hospital are screened for MRSA, but infection cannot always be prevented.
The sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented but the current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not favourable to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is most common in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients in hospital and isolate MRSA patients immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in vogue in Hungarian hospitals.
Please note that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases are only detected if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief medical officer of the Epidemiology Center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, in other words microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is spread from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
The Commission has also been consulted on the draft directive on the protection of workers from the risks related to exposure to ionising radiation.
MRSA is spread by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact, but due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, rooms are often full, beds are often too close together, while in terms of epidemics, patients should be kept at a distance of at least 1.5 meters from each other.
Unfortunately, we also see that hospitals in difficult financial situations are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, Karolina Böröcz said.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA is a huge expense for the social security funds, which is why the fight against this infection is everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this programme is effective and MRSA infections are showing a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified as one of its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The police commissioner, who was involved in a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official report on the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It is not possible that the 22nd arrondissement's commissioner, who has resigned since then, who ran over a pedestrian and killed him last Tuesday, was driving drunk or dizzy, Attila Morvai, spokesman for the capital's public prosecutor's office, said on Friday after the findings were made.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which had already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
On Tuesday, the former head of the 22nd arrondissement police station ran over a 55-year-old man who was facing him when he turned in his car on Kossuth Lajos Street in the 22nd arrondissement.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not a mitigating circumstance.
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following the accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and asked for his retirement because, according to the police communication, the accident had upset him greatly.
The investigation into this case is being conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates in charge of the investigation.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total of €400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, for which a EUR 100 million credit agreement has already been signed by the parties.
The agreement on the EUR 150 million loan also concerns budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, the remaining EUR 150 million of which will be available later, following the extension of the loan agreement.
The parties signed a €50 million innovation contract, which will be used by the state budget primarily for the research and development project at the University of Debrecen.
The negotiations also covered the project for metro line 4.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible modification of the original contract once Hungary had finalised the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could happen in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion to finance 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB provides loans at the Euribor rate, with an eight-year grace period and no commitment fee.
Bulgaria, the EU's housing market paradise
The Bulgarian real estate market is evolving dramatically, and the attention of all Europe is now focused on this Balkan country, which has been little mentioned in the past.
What, or who, bought on this EU market which is still the cheapest but which will soon become expensive?
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet decided whether the measure is compatible with the internal market.
Currently, Bulgaria is undoubtedly the hottest target in Eastern Europe for real estate with its cheap ski flats and seaside homes.
In the mountains, the most popular areas are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albena, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the old Sozopol and Nessebar but there are more and more people looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik area as well.
According to analysts from Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also attract the interest of investors and they are also increasingly buying in the cheap corner of Ruse.
The capital Sofia also offers attractive opportunities, with commercial and office space promising the highest rate of depreciation.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golfing paradises in Europe and thus a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
The more vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in the Bansko area.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are also looking to change their lives, their lifestyle.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and increasingly Romania.
The Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. e Black Sea and the most famous ski resorts are traditionally full of Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional manager of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to move in buy renovated buildings, which cost between 50 and 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, which cost between 5 and 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and generally the local doctor.
The second group includes second home buyers (since last December, Bulgaria has been listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group consists of commercial investors who buy in the hope of realising medium to long-term value.
The price of housing in the capital is constantly rising because of the increasing demand.
Bulgaria has the lowest real estate prices in the European Union, but over the past five years they have risen by 21 per cent a year.
The increase in house prices essentially outstrips the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Hungarian six percent
According to the communication by Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals will end on Tuesday, but on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to set out efforts to be made beyond the Kyoto Protocol's emissions reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there is a lively discussion on this subject between developing and developed countries.
The United States also indicated that it was not willing to discuss exact figures at this time, but was willing to sign an agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent by 2020 from 1990 levels.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need, in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund set up by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, likely to be part of the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister for the Environment and Water, confirmed the EU's ambition to remain a flagship in the overall efforts to protect the climate and to encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of whether the 'Post-2012 Agreement' was successfully signed, and was prepared to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also willing to make commitments commensurate with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997 the countries signatory to the Kyoto Protocol had set a total reduction target of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at the time had committed to 8 per cent less.
Hungary has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared with the 1985-87 period, and Hungary will fulfil its commitment, the Environment Ministry press release says.
The stakes are high in Bali because the international long-term climate agreement must be in place within two years, otherwise the agreement will certainly be postponed beyond 2012, in which case the reduction commitments below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be immediately followed by a new international emissions reduction system, the need for which was highlighted in the new report of the IPCC, the international scientific body that won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for dealing with climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth by more than 2 degrees Celsius would be unavoidable, which scientists say would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
The British Army is recruiting on YouTube
British Army units share video-sharing site footage of their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan in an attempt to gain popularity.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) became a fan of YouTube: Special Forces in Afghanistan uploaded video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken with miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at the Air Force operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to London where compatriots upload them to the Internet.
The political message is essential
The Air Force soldiers have already put 139 videos online through this channel and their "channel" has been watched by more than 75 thousand people.
The UK Ministry of Defence registered as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and it shares videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Force in Iraq (IPF) also have their own YouTube channels.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the Air Force's original goal, the videos were posted online for recruitment, and the Defense Ministry said they were also used to inform the general public about the real objectives of the military presence abroad.
Although propaganda by this means is relatively inexpensive compared with the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defense consultant, told the BBC, it also inevitably carries a political message, since it justifies in a special way the justification for military operations decided by the government.
The Americans have made a game
The army is annoyed because, in addition to the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have been posted on the sharing site that also show, for example, the death of soldiers: in the official propaganda films, a bit hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never show the bloody side of the battle.
In fact, many videos had already been posted online showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out in real-life operations, but the British Army only recently got excited about uploading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently using the free-to-download shooting game America's Army, in which the player can put himself directly in the soldiers' shoes in a more or less real simulation.
