The forces of the mega strike are gathering
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will form their strike committee on Friday to coordinate the indefinite strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, the day of the final vote on the health care bill, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause significant traffic jams as railway traffic will be almost completely stopped and BKV (public transport company) employees will also strike until 1 pm.
The unions will announce Friday afternoon the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers Councils.
The strike committee of LIGA-MOSZ will also be formed, it will serve as coordinator of the actions on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and from Monday, the organizations joining the strike will stop work indefinitely if they cannot reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, from the day of the vote in Parliament on the health insurance law, is not fixed.
If the National Assembly does not pass the law on health insurance, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, the strike committees will meet and decide what to do next.
According to the agenda of the National Assembly on Monday, the vote on the health insurance bill is likely to take place late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the planned strike on Monday, there will be significant traffic jams: railways will stop working indefinitely and in the morning some public transport in Budapest and more than half of Volán companies are at risk of being shut down.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half the road will also be blocked.
Many trade unions and civil society organisations have joined the call for strike action, and the list of these is updated regularly on the League's website.
Some organizations have announced an indefinite strike, others have announced a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon, the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Union of Railway Workers (VDSZSZ) were unable to reach an agreement on minimum services, and as the Christmas holidays approach, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, Budapest public transport will strike from the start of service until 1 pm, Budapest Airport between 7 am and 9 am, the Electricity and Heat Energy Industrial Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Democratic Teachers' Union have called for strikes for 2 hours and 2 hours to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Doctors will strike nationwide alternately, the Health and Social Workers' Union (EDDSZ) affiliated to the SZEF will strike a two-hour warning.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, demands that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to social debate.
The second demand is that the new method of calculating pensions to be introduced from next year be introduced in stages.
The third demand is a guarantee of early retirement, which would allow the rightful positions to be filled before 2010.
The fourth ground of appeal is the rejection by the Free Railway Workers' Union (VDSZSZ), affiliated to the League of Trade Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning secondary railway lines and the waiting for another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, which was formed in August last year with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozgalom (Movement for a Better Hungary), increases the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects.
In its  risk warning , the company points out that, in relation to the activity of the Hungarian Guard, the biggest political risk is already that  aggressive ethnic clashes may occur in the short term as a result of the worsening of the already existing ethnic tension between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population of Hungary .
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy, which is likely to cause this situation, is the main reason.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors:  public actors have passed on the public debate on the Roma issue to representatives of radical and extreme political groups who have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and the Hungarians .
The problem is aggravated, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are strengthened and aggressive conflicts are more likely to occur, they say.
However, according to the research institute, the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media  has significantly damaged Hungary's image abroad, particularly regarding confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity .
They recall that, following greater publicity given to the reorganisation of Hungarian radical and far-right groups since autumn 2006, numerous associations have been established in Hungary since summer 2007 under the name of  National Association of Self-Defense .
 The common feature of these meetings is that they define themselves as a civil organisation while they publicly declare the preparation of their members for defense missions (disasters, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, and also by referring to the inadequacy of the police, the army, in other words the state , they added.
They pointed out that everything was done according to the method which, based on the rancor of society of politics and parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions under a civilian aspect.
The emphasis on civil status and association status therefore serves not only to avoid the legal pitfalls of registering associations in court but also constitutes a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activity of the Hungarian Guard is a factor which also increases the risk in relation to neighbourhood relations.
 In recent months, many neighbouring countries have cited the Hungarian Guard as a potential source of risk and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighbouring countries want to justify their anti-Hungarian policies by referring to the constitution of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region, they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Central and Eastern Europe, political risks have increased throughout the region.
As they say, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard is similar, for example, to the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was declared by the Bulgarian National Union (BNU) in August 2007.
The many Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Kraszna Poljana) led to the establishment of the Bulgarian Guard.
Taking advantage of these events, the UNB decided to form a guard saying that the organization's goal is  national self-defense .
They say that for the past 17 years, the Gypsies have  terrorized  Bulgaria but the state has remained inactive and neutral, says Political Capital.
They added that the initiative had sparked a lively debate in Bulgarian public opinion.
They say that the statement by some Bulgarian Roma organizations about setting up their own guards as a resistance signals the increased risk of ethnic clashes.
The similarities between the Hungarian Guard and the Bulgarian National Guard do not exclude the possibility that Hungarian Roma may react to the threat in the same way by organizing their own self-defense, the risk warning from Political Capital says.
