In Hungary, the law defines the exact days of public holidays, and around the holidays it has become common to reorganize the working days, which will be reduced next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state holidays and rest days.
Holidays are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter especially so that the wakers can rest in peace.
In addition, we have a total of 11 red-marked holidays in a year.
March 15 is a national holiday, in commemoration of the 1848 revolution, as is October 23 which is also the commemoration day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20th, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1st is Labor Day, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our deceased family members and friends.
Besides, we have two days in Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
Since our national, state or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, depending on the calendar, it has become common to rearrange working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price for extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years the Minister of Labour has laid down special regulations on the days of substitution for the days before and after the holidays.
The law applies to all employers and all employees employed by them, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service companies, institutions which operate continuously and are in service by virtue of their vocation, and also to rest days.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24 onwards, life stops almost all over the country because experiments show that most people work overtime or take vacations they have saved for this purpose so that they can spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day at home.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The calendar will be rearranged for the first time around Labor Day to allow employees to stay home four days in a row.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day, so you will have a day off on Friday 2 May.
Another change is planned for 23 October: Saturday 18 October will be a working day replacing Friday 24.
But next year, the end of the year is coming with the holidays because from December 24 onwards, everyone will take a non-stop break even if New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
Six trivial things that can be a huge annoyance to coworkers
E-mails we forget to send, voice messages we never get, innocent lies that almost annoy us more: these are things that  beautify  a workplace's daily life.
The question is whether we get used to these problems or whether we rise to the challenge and consciously avoid ambiguous situations that cause trouble for others.
Examples.
I'm sorry, I forgot to tell you that you got a call from the marketing department.
That you missed a date?
At best, he's sorry and tries to make things right by calling the marketing department and telling them he forgot to pass the message (the least common solution).
In most cases, the matter is settled with an apology.
Before giving hurtful explanations, it is helpful to think about how you can cause unpleasant situations for your workmates and to work to avoid them.
You're borrowing something that doesn't belong to you?
There's nothing more annoying than wanting to grab a file or a desk tool or a phone and you can't find them anywhere.
Remember the day before you put the stapler on the desk but it was gone the next morning?
You wouldn't happen to find your pen you thought you lost on your colleague's desk?
Don't take anything from your coworkers without asking, or they're right to be angry at you for stealing their property.
Don't bring envelopes home, just mail them in your pocket because it can be annoying when they're gone and you need them right away.
You're talking about the private lives of your colleagues?
There are no good ways to stop gossip from spreading.
Who did what, with who?
Or why?
Do not tell everyone your information (assumptions) about the privacy of your colleagues!
If a coworker confides in you, do not abuse his trust.
Keep the shared information to yourself and don't discuss it with your coworkers in his absence even if your coworkers know about it.
You're calling yourself sick for no good reason?
When you call the office and you call in sick on the pretext of a debilitating headache because you feel sick or you feel you need to rest that day, think about the fact that your work, your urgent business, your deadline assignments need to be done by someone else for you.
Don't bother your coworkers!
If you know in advance that you will not be at work the next day or that something may happen that will require you to stay at home, be sure to tell your boss and coworkers so that they do not be surprised when you are not at work the next day.
The whining, the laughing, the phone
You're so busy with your work, but the laughter of your colleagues suddenly pulls you away?
Have you unwittingly become a witness to a phone conversation that you should have ignored?
Don't disturb your coworkers with humming, singing, talking out loud (over their heads), kicking, swearing, or loudly expressing complaints.
They can be annoying even if your colleagues are not involved in a project - writing, designing, organizing.
You blame others for a mistake?
If you're late with your work, forget to send an important e-mail or text, don't blame anyone for that.
Don't blame him for the mess in the office or the noisy coworkers!
If you have committed a mistake and caused others to suffer, admit it and correct the mistake.
Ask how you can make up for your mistake, correct your negligence.
Do you feel too comfortable in the office?
Wearing jogging boots and slippers is comfortable at home but they don't fit in the office!
Don't wear comfortable jogging shoes even if your job allows it!
Don't be neglected, respect your coworkers and yourself by dressing properly, and if your job requires it by wearing nice, fancy clothes to go to work.
