So everything is all right ?
hvg.hu has asked Balázs Zságer questions.
hvg.hu: This new hit makes me ask a question: has your music really remained a music aimed at a certain layer?
Zságer Balázs: The term music aimed at a certain layer doesn't mean much to me.
For me, there are two castes in light music; not mainstream or underground, not alternative or pop but commercial music and sincere music.
So-called alternative, underground music can also be mediocre and made just to sell and thus become commercial.
But a good pop song can also be sincere.
The attitude of reception works in this spirit also regardless of language or borders.
hvg.hu: Do you see a difference between the Hungarian and foreign audience, is one or the other more open to your music?
ZsB: Overseas, especially in the West, light music has older traditions.
There, people go to concerts and not only the young people in their 10s and 20s but also the older ones.
They are much more attentive to the changes in light music because they think it is also part of contemporary culture.
hvg.hu: What is the role of the public in your work?
Are you interested in who, or how many people, are listening to your music?
ZsB: I'm obviously happy to see more and more people coming to our concerts.
However, we never made music for the market.
For us, music is not made to achieve a goal but for a specific reason.
The role of the audience is more important at concerts where the mutual influence is already working but is only perceived in the elusive changes of the moment.
Now, I've noticed that if you try to live up to the expectations of the public, you're not going to be interesting.
hvg.hu: Do you plan to follow Yonderboi's example?
He works alone and has made a career out west.
ZsB: We don't really follow his path, although sometimes some people try to find traces in our music.
We're more like team players who trust each other's musical presence and let it unfold.
At first, it was inevitable that our music would be compared to Yonderboi's because many of us left his band and went our separate ways.
hvg.hu: On the mr2 Petõfi list, Wings of Love is number one.
Many people have heard the name Zagar for the first time through this song.
With this more popular style you've consciously opened up to a wider layer?
ZsB: We didn't plan on making a hit record to sell the record.
This song means more than that.
We wanted it for the end of the album to try and soften the orgy of sounds and the more difficult themes that are covered throughout the record.
hvg.hu: How did you choose the six singers?
Why did they - what was the guideline?
ZSB: The idea was to have a gospel choir.
We had the idea of composing this choir of good soloists from the Hungarian music scene.
The choir was made up of six members, Sena, Edina Kutzora, Judie Jay, Bori Péterfy, Enikõ Hodosi [Neo], Juci Németh, who later became known as the Underground Divas.
hvg.hu: Did you want this song like this or did the girls change it a little?
ZsB: This song had already existed for a long time in an instrumental version and then when we composed the album, we thought that there was still something missing from this song.
The chord sequence drew the voice of the song.
I sang the song that night, the melody the girls learned later.
I had it almost immediately and it was all terribly spontaneous.
I remember it galvanized me at the time but sure enough we needed the Divas.
She wouldn't have had the same strength with my voice.
hvg.hu: On the record and at the concert too, it seemed to me that the girls were in the background.
There are no solos (except for a brief Judy Jay solo), they don't have a solo role, they all sing together and they don't sing louder than the music, so the music doesn't just accompany their singing.
They were backstage, too.
Is that what you want?
ZsB: The fact that they were in the background is due to technical problems alone.
But what was voluntary was that we didn't want to distribute solo roles.
The song also says that we need to forget our ego a little bit, forget who's coming from where, who's going or, we just need to let these wings, the wings of love, carry us away.
I wanted others to feel the same euphoric state we felt when the song was born.
hvg.hu: Which of the songs did you work on the most?
ZS: Actually, none of it was about the process of creating music, we had more difficult pieces when mixing.
For example, with Dorian Gray's Dilemma, or I'm playing piano in concert, or with Rock 'n' Roll Goes To The Girls, or the groove didn't want to work for a long time, and then, little by little, it all came together like a puzzle.
hvg.hu: What's your favorite song on the new album?
ZSB: It changes all the time with the concerts and the fact that I've already released this record.
Right now, it's Prophet Is A Fool, Escape From The Earth and Never The Same.
The treacherous trader risked billions because of his inferiority complex
A fraud in disguise.
This is how the former employee of the French giant Societe Generale, owner of the Czech bank Komerční banka, is described.
The bank lost almost five billion euros because of him.
It seems rather that Kerviel is just a great player who wanted to match his colleagues, and who, moreover, can by no means be considered incapable.
