The crisis extends beyond the United States
"All I wanted was to make money for my bank", he says in the deposition.
Last summer, he managed to take advantage of the American crisis to make half a billion euros.
In fact, he felt the opportunity earlier this year.
Reports began to emerge in February that so-called sub-prime mortgages, granted to low-income customers or those who had had difficulties in repayment in the past, would have problems.
But this crisis should not affect the whole economy.
Kerviel didn't believe in it, and he bet it well.
Thus, at the end of the year, its profits amounted to EUR 1.6 billion.
"As soon as I won my first half-billion, I didn't know how to announce it", says Kerviel, adding that he, of course, kept nothing to himself.
Throughout the interrogation, he admits to falsifying the reports to avoid detection.
He managed to fool his superiors, although the Eurex exchange began to take an interest in his transactions.
Who risks nothing has nothing
Was he afraid of being discovered?
I'm not sure.
"I figured the mere fact of getting 1.6 billion for the bank would satisfy them".
Why is he willing to risk so much?
He only got to his post gradually.
He had started working at Société Générale in 2000 just after finishing his studies at the University of Lyon.
His annual salary was around $51,000.
Two years later, he was already an assistant trader, and in 2005, he became a freelance trader with an annual salary of $90,000.
But he knew that he would never earn as much as the others.
"From my first interview in 2005, I knew I was being treated far less favorably than others.
In view of my university education and my professional and personal background", Kerviel told investigators.
Soon after he took office, however, he achieved his first major success.
Thanks to Allianz shares, he made half a billion euros betting on the decline of that stock during the London bombings.
