The spectacular repair on the space station
It took astronaut Scott Parazynski and his fellow crew members on the International Space Station (ISS) more than seven hours of space work to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, vital to the station's continued scientific activities.
A risky outing that has set records for its duration, its distance from habitable modules, the speed with which it was conceived, the tools  handcrafted  by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose on Tuesday when the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module, a large cylindrical piece of spacecraft that will soon house European and Japanese science laboratories.
This module is a kind of docking station for the lab modules.
But we have to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was to move a 17.5-ton solar power module already on the ISS to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began re-deploying the module's 76-meter-wide solar arrays.
And that's where one of the panels, which unfolds like accordions, was damaged by a cable that got stuck for almost a meter.
The deployment was stopped to avoid further damage to the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally scheduled to make a control exit from the shuttle Discovery and then go to repair another solar panel that had a faulty rotation system, were forced to focus on the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go to the end of the 100-foot long remote control arm of the shuttle that was added to the station's to perform the repair.
He is one of NASA's best spacewalkers.
Tall, tough, very skilled, with a very developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this trained doctor was assigned to  operate  the solar panel  injured .
After carefully inspecting the damage, he cut the faulty cable and installed some sort of  splints  on the damaged area.
He was assisted by a second spacewalker who remained near the airlock and, from inside, by the other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the crew commander.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick wrapped in insulation to prevent electric shock on solar panels that generated several hundred volts, was designed and crafted  by the astronauts on board the station.
When the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited for the panel to be fully deployed before taking inventory of his tools and returning to the interior of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts returned to the shuttle Discovery for a scheduled return to Earth on Wednesday.
