A painful memory
After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives in Bad Arolsen, which record the fate of 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are now open to the public.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on a 27 km line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were previously only accessible for  humanitarian  purposes, i.e. on an individual and nominative basis, at the request of a former victim or his beneficiaries.
The 11 countries responsible for their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them up to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of the agreement by all States is complete and the opening of the Convention has been in effect since yesterday.
The information shall be sensitive.
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research  on the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health of forced labourers , explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the public disclosure of such personal data, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some of the deportation victims.
The Gestapo's records of concentration camps and arrest warrants were compiled after the war for a practical purpose: to locate civilians deported or forced to work and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, so as to pave the way for compensation.
Today, in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees still handle tens of thousands of individual claims.
However, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest to some in the scientific community.
 There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents, said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
