What kind of insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which covers the driver against possible accidents, involves a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, gender, age of the driver's license, civil status, type of vehicle insured or use, and others.
Having a car is the main thing.
It is even more difficult to choose the right car insurance than to choose the right model of vehicle.
And it is that choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is made in the form of an insurance contract, which stipulates that the company receives the value of the premium and in return becomes liable for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a loss.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is determined by various factors, such as age, gender, driving licence age, marital status, type of vehicle to be insured or use, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices based on statistics, so that the higher the likelihood of an accident, the higher the premium.
For this reason, people over 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that these people have a lower rate of claims due to their caution.
Similarly, using surveys, companies have concluded that married drivers tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency and therefore the likelihood of an accident.
The more frequent the odds increase.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when setting the premium price.
This is why the driver must carefully consider the situation to choose the car insurance that best suits his profile.
We will outline the most important variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it not only adapts to the insurer's characteristics but also offers a reasonable price.
Young people under 25 face a number of disadvantages when purchasing affordable insurance, such as low driving experience and long driving licenses.
Although the ideal insurance policy is a risk-free policy, there are other cheaper options.
The more prudent drivers can choose to take out a risk-free policy with confidence, so that they can get the coverage of a risk-free policy at a more affordable price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays part of the claim amount.
"The part of the claim amount that the customer pays will be determined by the value of the premium, which will be higher the lower the amount", says Luis Noguera, the head in Spain of First Europa, an online insurance broker.
Another option is extended third party insurance, so that the customer insures protection against damage caused to third parties, but not for those caused to his own car.
In addition, it would be insured against theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
I'll give you a piece of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid accidents as much as possible, as this will affect the bonus, which may lower the price of the insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction in the basic fare of the company.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
"The bonuses and penalties will depend on the company and its profit.
If the company has had a good year, it can afford to increase the bonuses", explains Noguera.
After the age of 25, it becomes easier for drivers to take out insurance, since the accident rate is reduced by accumulated experience.
For this reason, it is best to choose a risk-free insurance policy with honesty.
"Young people usually don't get the benefit of the experience they have gained after an accident", says the European company's manager in Spain, adding that most accidents occur in the second year of driving, after the 'fear of the novice' is over.
However, if the customer is married but has no children yet, it is preferable to negotiate an all-risk insurance policy, as long as his economic situation allows it.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be the ones with the lowest claims rate, because the premiums will be lower.
In this case, the best insurance would be an all-risk insurance with deductible (up to EUR 300), or an extended third party insurance from the third year of the vehicle's life when the insured has a high level of bonus.
"They have more relaxed driving and they have more purchasing power to afford the luxury of taking on a larger amount of franchisees", says Luis Noguera.
For pensioners, an all-risk insurance with deductible is preferable (at €150), or an extended third party insurance when the insurer has a high level of bonus.
It must be said that car insurance is important, not only because it covers the driver against possible accidents, but also because it is a considerable expense, so it is essential to properly study the insurance that is most suitable for us according to our personal situation.
