Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to Earth's, and may even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect from carbon dioxide, the atmospheric erosion from solar radiation, coupled with a slower rotation, has led Venus to a whole other kind of evolution.
Today the planet is without water, ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms, and has a surface temperature hot enough to melt lead.
The findings of the Venus Express probe of the European Space Agency, which studied the planet for a year, offer a bleak glimpse of the potential future of the Earth due to catastrophic climate change.
