But now a revelation that a wealthy businessman had hidden for four years, under false names, his contributions to the current Labour Party, equivalent to over £650,000 ($1.3m), which the party did not declare: another battle that Gordon Brown would have gotten away with.
Two months ago, the Prime Minister backtracked on his election plan, foolishly insulting British intelligence by proclaiming that opinion polls had not influenced his decision, and that he hoped instead to offer a compact and effective government.
On the contrary, Vince Cable, the brilliant Liberal Democrat leader, said that the terrifying Mr. Brown had turned from Stalin into Mr. Bean.
The purchase of Northern Rock, a struggling bank on the brink of bankruptcy, demonstrated a flaw in the guidelines and poor judgment in an emergency.
Inadequate proposals for a change in the tax code have led to a coalition of industrial groups against the government.
The loss of 25 million personal data by the IRS has revealed an incredible administrative blunder.
A trio of retired generals have launched a rebellion in the House of Lords, protesting against cuts in military spending. They have proclaimed that being Secretary of State for Defence is for them a part-time job.
At the moment, suspicion of shady donations from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour General Secretary (and his former head of vigilance) have forced them to resign.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is bound to head for the exit.
But governments can get to a point where it is impossible to govern.
People don't like politicians, and they don't trust them, but they usually put their doubts aside when a new government comes to power.
It seems obvious that a prime minister cannot improve things, or even govern for long, when he is at risk of suspension: the public administration is no longer functioning; the cabinets of ministers are being assessed; the press is looking for bad news; and the government becomes defensive and has no further objective.
In a sense, Mr Brown's position is particularly difficult, because unlike other political leaders, he cannot boast of being a beginner.
Although he would like to repudiate Tony Blair, he was still his senior lieutenant.
The problems relating to Northern Rock and tax data, for example, are linked to decisions made by Mr Brown when he was Chancellor of the Exchequer.
And even if he is not directly involved in Blair's misfortunes, such as the long investigation into party funds  cash for members of the House of Lords , voters might think otherwise.
But Mr Brown's predicament is not as tragic as it seems.
The blunders are not as monstrous as Tory Party members make them out to be.
Just like Mr. Bean, there are no victims and no scams.
And the remedy, though painful, could be to put into practice Mr Brown's longstanding Stalinist tendencies for a reliable and slightly brutal government.
The recent political donation scandal is a good example.
Mr. Abrahams, a very particular character who compares his donations to charity, said he did not want any public recognition of his charity.
He may have his own opinion, but it's not his decision.
The laws against the anonymity of big donors to politicians are clear, and they exist for a good reason: The public has a right to know who contributes to the success of those who will rule the country.
Mr Watt, who said he knew about Mr Abrahams's programmes, without knowing that they were illegal, will therefore have to be questioned, as will Jon Mendlesohn, the fund-raiser manager who spoke of the dubious donations in October.
But so far Mr Brown has not been involved: there is no indication that he was aware of these moves, even though most of the payments were made after he joined the government in June.
So far the Prime Minister has done half.
He was quick to condemn his party's legislative flaw, but he failed to draw attention to the fact that the decision-making power rests on something he knows well, to call upon a committee of inquiry on this subject made up of a retired bishop and a judge.
In that case, the lessons to be learned are not complicated.
And if the law has been broken, it's the police's responsibility.
In addition, there are many other things Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman for the Independent Standards Committee on Public Life, which has been without a leader for six months, and preparing a good reform of political party finances.
This would force the Labour Party, in a moment of weakness, to collaborate with the Tories, which could lead to it giving up its particular financial relationship with the confederations; in short, a bitter pill for a supporter such as Mr Brown.
But he should face some favorable facts.
The Conservative Party now has a good electoral advantage; it has two years to win back the electorate, and the only way to win is to demonstrate impeccable integrity and strong skills.
