Could the mortgage crisis contaminate the U.S. credit card market?
When there's blood in the water, it's normal to see fins flailing around.
Now that the U.S. housing market is going through a critical phase, predators are targeting the U.S. credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs believe credit card losses could reach $99 billion if the contagion spreads from mortgages to other forms of consumer credit.
There are obvious signs of tension.
There are increases in the rates of fees and insolvency, which measures the parts of the balance sheet that are not recoverable or are, more than 30 days later.
HSBC announced last month that it took $1.4 billion in consumer loans, partly because of weak cardholders.
It's still too early to panic.
The costs and insolvencies are still moderate.
According to Moody's, a tax agency, the third-quarter insolvency rate of 3.89 percent is almost one percentage point below its historical average.
The deterioration in rates is partly explained by technical factors.
A change in the laws in 2005 in the United States regarding personal bankruptcy caused a sharp drop in bankruptcy records, which in turn caused heavy losses for credit cards; the number of records (and thus insolvency rates) could increase even if loan conditions worsened.
The industry also advertises fixed payment rates, which highlight the amount of debt consumers have to pay each month.
and confidence in the security of credit card capital is quite strong despite the paralysis of other aspects of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicted that the volume of emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
