British bankers plead guilty to the Enron case.
The three British bankers who were due to testify in connection with a fraud committed by Enron's former chief financial officer, Andrew Fastow, changed their plea to guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had originally pleaded not guilty to seven counts of alleged collusive fraud in 2000, committed by Fastow in a secret financial scam to enrich himself at the expense of their employees.
They're due in court in January.
But at a hearing presided over by U.S. Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., they all pleaded guilty to fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the PLC group of the Royal Bank of Scotland, became famous throughout Britain because of the extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, their case remains an open question for this investigation, which began after the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges against them in 2002 made it clear to Fastow that he was the subject of the government's investigation into the Enron debacle.
The charges against the bankers, dubbed the "Natwest Three", state that they came to Houston in 2000 to stage a fraudulent script with Fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the mastermind behind many fraudulent scenarios, which helped him rig bankruptcy proceedings.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the branch as zero, but in fact the three Britishmen already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank's interest in the subsidiary for £1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 in interest on this company.
According to the indictment, Fastow falsely told Enron that the energy company was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich NatWest for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in reality, that $20 million went into the pockets of British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the indictment, the bankers were paid $7.3 million while Fastow, Kopper and the others were paid $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in the Enron debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a three-year, one-month sentence in a Texas prison.
The three British nationals were released on bail of $1 million each, which requires them to live in the United States during the trial.
Enron, once the seventh largest national corporation, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of accounting fraud, could no longer hide its billions in debt or even offer its bogus speculation as profitable.
The collapse caused thousands of layoffs, over $60 billion in lost market value and over $2 billion in lost pension plans.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year of their involvement in the company's collapse.
Skilling was sentenced to more than 24 years in prison.
Charges against Lay for conspiracy, fraud and other crimes were dropped because of his death from a heart attack last year.
