Everyone is hoping that the Federal Reserve will lower rates in the wake of the global stock market bubble.
Stocks exploded on both sides of the Atlantic yesterday after the market hoped the Federal Reserve would try to calm credit conditions, subsequently lowering interest rates spurred by the soothing statements of the US central bank's vice president.
Stock markets are exploding in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second only to Ben Bernanke, chairman of the Federal Reserve, said that decision makers must be  flexible and pragmatic  in their actions in the turbulent financial markets.
In an apparent effort to reassure the volatile markets in the face of new credit tensions, Kohn said the recent turbulence had partly reversed some improvements in market performance in late September and October.
If this severe turbulence were to persist, it would increase the likelihood of further rigid financial conditions for owners and businesses, he said.
These comments are seen by investors as a clear signal that the Federal Reserve is ready to inject new capital into US markets, and that further interest rate cuts could stabilize credit conditions.
These comments also helped to calm Wall Street with even worse news about the US economy, such as the biggest drop in property sales for the month of October.
The impact of this financial turmoil was exacerbated by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would lay off 650 people, or 4% of its staff, to reduce costs to compensate for the heavy losses from losing bets on real estate loans.
Only 20 positions are planned in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 331 points, or 2.55%, to close at 13,289.40, while the largest index, the S&P 500, rose 2.65%.
In London, the FTSE 100 index rose 165.5 points or 2.7% to 6306.2, adding more than £39 to the value of British companies.
The German Dax index rose by 2.6% and the French CAC40 rose by 2.3%.
Earlier, the resurgence of credit difficulties on the markets was highlighted by the strong demand for an auction of monthly tri-monthly funds issued by the European Central Bank, which cut these loans to European commercial banks at a hefty rate of 4.7%, the highest since April 2001.
Pressures on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and the ECB and inject additional funds into London's financial markets, causing credit tensions, have caused the UK banks' monthly borrowing rates  Libor to grow at their highest since September last year, to 6.59% after a sharp rise since 12 November.
