Little Saar, good training.
The smallest federal state is a leader in vocational training and even stands out for the international orientation of its higher education institutions.
The Sarrois are in a deficit in one area only, which is similar to the rest of the country.
"I explained yesterday for the 50th time to a non-Sarrois that we are not French" - this is the slogan that the smallest federal state, out of self-deprecation, is displaying for its 50th anniversary.
In this respect, France and Luxembourg play a major role in the training system in the Saarland, which is ranked fifth in the training monitor of the German Economic Institute in Cologne.
Thus, higher education institutions have traditionally cooperated closely with neighbouring countries.
The university was founded in 1948 by the French in Saarbrücken.
To date, students have the opportunity to complete their studies with a double or even triple degree.
This is evidenced by the high percentage of foreign students, 15.6 per cent.
The Saarland also sends more than the average number of children to higher education - many of them without a high school diploma.
"In Saarland, the vocational training system is being used", says Axel Plünnecke, training expert at IW.
More than one in five young people obtain their qualifications in a vocational school, so Saarland is more than seven points above the national average.
The possibilities for combining vocational and academic training are therefore relatively well developed.
In terms of population, the dual-education panel is the second best in Germany.
Despite practical training and growing demand, however, the number of graduates in engineering has fallen by a third in recent years.
This is why the Saarland Ministry of Education has forced higher education institutions to launch a marketing campaign in engineering science subjects.
"After the first PISA studies, we have seen a lot of reforms in the general schools", says a spokeswoman for the Ministry of Education.
The government has introduced comparative tests throughout the state.
To help children start learning earlier, the last year of preschool is tax-free - a model that other states are now copying.
Only future comparative studies will be able to show whether pupil performance improves in a lasting way.
