Venus is the Earth's infernal twin.
Despite its inhospitable atmosphere, Venus is more Earthlike than previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirlpools at the poles, similar to those seen on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have speculated that there are lightning on Venus.
The European probe Venus Express has now provided proof - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: lightning on Venus is flashing from a height of about 35 miles [56 km] in cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles, in the scientific journal Nature.
According to the famous cypress theory, lightning would have brought life to Earth. The storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
"If life existed, it must have been very early in history", says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
There should be little life on the surface of Venus today. The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperatures can reach 500 degrees Fahrenheit.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it is still a twin", said Russell.
Why Venus, which is so similar to Earth in mass and size, was struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of the "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in the search for Venus, since no spacecraft had been on its way to explore the planet since the 1990s.
According to the researchers, the latest research results now presented in several articles in Nature do more than just highlight the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
They also show that our neighboring planet has more in common with Earth than was initially thought.
For example, researchers found that in addition to the winds already known at the North Pole, a clouds' whirlwind at the South Pole is spinning much faster.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system is almost as massive as the earth and is almost as large, with a diameter of 12,000 miles [12,100 km].
The planet, called the evening or morning star, orbits the sun in just 225 days.
It does, however, rotate much more slowly around itself: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, bears little resemblance to Earth, scientists speculate that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth as oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has been trapped on Earth as carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
