Richard Gere is simply not cynical enough.
With "The Hunting Party" and "Killer Peace", two films again address the Balkan war.
But neither of them are convincing.
Either the plans are too much based on action and senseless exchanges of fire or they are too tearful.
Here, even Richard Gere in "The Hunting Party" can't help you.
The good news first: although the war criminals Karadzic and Mladic are still hiding in the Balkan mountains, it is precisely there, in the most gloomy backcountry of the Bosnian war, that actor Richard Gere is found.
We had finally lost sight of the handsomest man of the 1980s, because far too many gentle and trivial roles in women's-feeling films and far too many press conferences on the subject of Buddhism had made him want to show off.
Today Richard Gere is suddenly the most important argument for watching "The Hunting Party" anyway - when the hunter becomes the hunted (why do today's movies have to be as long and confusing as collective conventions of locomotive drivers?)
He delivers a beautiful, wink-filled portrayal: at bottom, his character of war reporter Simon Hunt is what Gere might have become, had fate and the film industry not been so kind: a man whose best moments have long been behind him, but who, even as a ruined monument in decline, has nevertheless kept visible remnants of his former charm.
But despite this, "The Hunting Party" continues along with the German production "Killer Peace", which also releases this week, the endless series of failed films about the Balkan war.
"Murder Peace" can be quickly put on trial: the film is about two German soldiers in Kosovo (Adrian Topol, Max Riemelt), who rescue a Serbian woman from Kosovo snipers, in whom one of them quickly falls in love.
Although it is welcome that for once the Serbs are not being portrayed as the sole cause of all the ills, this film, which is as flat as a TV movie, is lost far too quickly in the action and senseless gun battles.
It's still kind of a "Cobra 11 Alert" without the highway but with a war in place.
On the contrary, we can examine in the perfect example of "The Hunting Party" why there never was a really good film about the Balkan war.
The story of three American war reporters, who condition themselves to track down the top war criminal "the fox", might have become, with another director and another screenwriter (both Richard Shepard), at another time a new "Apocalypse Now".
Because the stories are strikingly similar: two males go into the forest in small teams, to accomplish something that the military can't, and for both males, it becomes a journey into madness.
One of the reasons "The Hunting Party" failed is that we simply don't let Simon Hunt be the desolate cynic with a heart, as he is presented to us at the beginning.
No, the script must also credit him with a romantic affair with a Bosnian woman who was later murdered.
Then "The Hunting Party" becomes definitely bad, when the reporter, in the last five minutes, by a fast-track process, does what NATO, CIA and all the bounty hunters in the world have failed to do in five years: catch the war criminal and leave him to exact just revenge on the Bosnian Muslims.
It's so bad that we should take it to the International Criminal Court in The Hague for violating cinematic logic.
In this case, the film has a too deep human concern.
He wants to denounce that Karadzic and Mladic are still at large, and he suspects the Americans and the French (in this they must exceptionally agree) are not conducting the hunt intensively enough because of secret political agreements.
But the good-intentioned and the bad-intentioned are so similar this time that a famous Brecht poem comes to mind.
It tells of a wooden mask of an Asian demon on the poet's desk: "Compassionate, I see the veins of the forehead swollen, clearly: how tiring it is to be evil".
Movies like "The Hunting Party" have exactly that kind of tumbled heads, but they hint at how tiresome it is to be good.
The problem is not limited to the kind of films about the Balkan wars.
Recently, it was reported in this newspaper that all Hollywood films about Iraq were huge flops.
We can add that there have never been any good films about South Africa.
Which is always true: when a star hangs out in a crisis home or a minefield, he then comes out with something like "Rangoon" with Patricia Arquette, "Jenseits aller Grenzen" with Angelina Jolie or "Blutdiamanten" with Leonardo DiCaprio.
It is possible that all these conflicts are still simply too close in time.
Anyway, it was always decades before Hollywood could make a good Holocaust movie with "Schindler's List".
Some films have yet to mature - those that are now considered classics about Vietnam - "The Deer Hunter", "Apocalypse Now" or "Full Metal Jacket" were by no means universally celebrated as masterpieces in their day.
But maybe we also know too much about the conflicts of the world today, where every massacre happens live on two screens at home at the same time,
And it robs screenwriters of the lack of scruples they need to tell good stories.
"To Be or Not to Be" or "The Dictator" actually became so good also because Lubtisch and Chaplin didn't yet know how dominating the Nazi regime really was.
Maybe you don't want to be good when you want to make good movies.
Maybe we should have the sarcastic, distant artistic gaze of novelist Lawrence Norfolk.
