These aren't Warhol's boxes.
If you connect the concepts of Sweden and wooden box, you think of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast a shadow over Warhol's list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes a few months ago, internal research at Moderna Museet Stockholm has now led to a disappointing result: the six Brillo-Boxes, which the former director of the museum Pontus Hulten gave to Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - along with a large part of the hundreds of other Brillo-Boxes of the "Stockholm Type" that circulate on the international art market.
Ancient history is a tangled web of artistic and curatorial production.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York City, painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" soap boxes.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 featured - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather models of them, exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to have some Brillo wooden crates produced in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time now speak of about fifteen wooden crates which at the time would have gone down in art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol Brillo-Boxes, with the designation "Type Stockholm".
Some of these have been auctioned for over $100,000.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén museum later falsely claimed that about a hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later sell to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén cases were produced in Malmö in 1990 alone for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator at Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the six Brillo-Boxes in the museum, three others from Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of the white oil paint.
The texture of the 1990 copies reveals that the paint was applied directly, without a backing, to the laminated panels using a roll of paint - and not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorised by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes", suggests Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet. "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not reach a different decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exhibition material".
The Authentication Board, of course, announced in July that it would investigate the "heavy allegations" in the case of the soap boxes.
But since then, there's been an inexorable silence.
